      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A planetary conjunction occurs when two planets appear close together in the sky, but don't actually collide. This is usually due to the perspective from Earth, where the planets are at similar distances from their respective suns and are often visible in the same part of the sky. Orbital inclination plays a role, as planets with higher inclinations (tilts) will intersect more often due to their differing orbital paths. This effect can make the conjunction appear closer or wider on the sky.",
